mily Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (North and West Midlands): habitational name from any of various places called Whiston (in Yorkshire, Lancashire, Northamptonshire, and two places in Staffordshire), or from Wiston in Sussex. The Yorkshire and Lancashire placenames derive from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’; Whiston near Cheadle (Staffordshire) has the same etymology. Whiston near Penkridge (Staffordshire) derives from an Old English personal name <i>Witi</i> (genitive <i>Wites</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The Northamptonshire placename derives from the Old English tribal name <i>Hwicce</i> (genitive <i>Hwiccena</i>) + <i>tūn</i>, or perhaps from an Old English personal name <i>Hwicca</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Sussex placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wīgstan</i> (genitive <i>Wīgstanes</i>) + <i>tūn</i>. Sometimes this name is a variant of   Whitestone  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Whitestone","meanings":["English (Leicestershire) and Scottish: habitational name from Whitstone (Cornwall), Whitestone (Devon) or Whitestone Farm in Birdham (Sussex). In Scotland it may be from Whiteston (Perthshire) or Whitestone (Birse, Aberdeenshire), but the surname may not have survived in Scotland. The placenames derive from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’ or their later Scots equivalents. Alternatively, a variant of   Whiston  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Whiston was born about 1450, in Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Mrs Robert Whiston about 1470, in Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1450–":"umbes 1450–Surnud","1452–Female":"1452–Surnud","1460–1529":"1460–1529","1450–Male":"1450–Surnud","Abt 1450":"umbes 1450","Abt 1470":"umbes 1470","1452":"1452","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1529":"1529","Cottonham, Cambridge, England":"Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"Abt 1450–":"noin 1450–Kuollut","1452–Female":"1452–Kuollut","1460–1529":"1460–1529","1450–Male":"1450–Kuollut","Abt 1450":"noin 1450","Abt 1470":"noin 1470","1452":"1452","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1529":"1529","Cottonham, Cambridge, England":"Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England"},"fr":{"Abt 1450–":"environ 1450–Décédé","1452–Female":"1452–Décédée","1460–1529":"1460–1529","1450–Male":"1450–Décédé","Abt 1450":"environ 1450","Abt 1470":"environ 1470","1452":"1452","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1529":"1529","Cottonham, Cambridge, England":"Cambridgeshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Whiston est né environ 1450, à Cambridgeshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Mrs Robert Whiston environ 1470, à Cambridgeshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"Abt 1450–":"um 1450–Verstorben","1452–Female":"1452–Verstorben","1460–1529":"1460–1529","1450–